<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is knitting gauge?", answer: "Knitting gauge is the number of stitches and rows per a measured area of knitted fabric, usually expressed as stitches and rows per 4 inches (10 cm). Gauge depends on your yarn, needle size, stitch pattern, and personal tension. Matching a pattern's gauge is essential for the finished garment to come out the size the designer intended." },
  { question: "Why is my gauge different from the pattern?", answer: "Every knitter has a unique tension that affects how tight or loose their stitches are. Even with the exact yarn and needles a pattern calls for, you may get more or fewer stitches per inch. To match a pattern's gauge, go up a needle size if your gauge has too many stitches per inch (fabric too tight), or down a size if you have too few (fabric too loose)." },
  { question: "Should I wash my swatch before measuring?", answer: "Yes. Always wash and block your swatch the same way you will treat the finished garment. Many yarns, especially natural fibers like wool and cotton, change significantly after washing. Measuring an unblocked swatch can lead to a finished garment that is inches off from the intended size after its first wash." },
  { question: "What if I'm between needle sizes?", answer: "If the closest match to your target gauge falls between two needle sizes, try the smaller size first and knit a fresh swatch. If the fabric feels too dense, go up. Gauge can also be adjusted slightly by changing stitch pattern, but needle size is the primary lever." },
  { question: "How big should my swatch be?", answer: "Cast on enough stitches to measure a flat 6-inch square at minimum, ideally larger. Stitches near the edges distort, so measuring 4 inches in the center of a 6-inch swatch gives a more accurate reading than measuring across the entire piece." }
]) %>

